ndwork for Ibn al-'Arabi's unique concept of barzakh. Bashier discusses Ibn al-'Arabi's development of the concept of barzakh ontologically through the notion of the Third Thing and epistemologically through the notion of the Perfect Man, and compares Ibn al-'Arabi's vision with Plato's.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCreation (Islam). 0aIntermediate statexIslam. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Mysticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791484340423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791484340/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles